<p>This was no leisure craft. It carried a turret-mounted 50 caliber Browning machine gun and had racks that could carry up four torpex-filled MK-47 depth bombs (350 lbs. each). These airships were deployed by the Navy to help search for and destroy enemy submarines. The airship included a ASG-type radar system capable of detecting objects at 90 miles and sonobuoys used to probe for submerged submarines. </p><figure><iframe width="200" height="150" src="https://www.youtube-nocookie.com/embed/B0SYRukm6y0?feature=oembed" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen="" sandbox="allow-scripts allow-same-origin allow-popups" loading="lazy"></iframe><figcaption>Footage of a K-Class airship dropping depth charges on suspected submarines at sea on December 14, 1943.</figcaption></figure><p>On July 31, 1943, The New York Times <a href="https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1943/07/31/85112859.html?pageNumber=6&amp;ref=beautiful-public-data" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">reported</a> that airship K-74 was shot down over the Atlantic, after a U-boat it had been hunting with depth charges surfaced, and shot it down. All but one member of the crew survived the splashdown in the ocean. </p><figure><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/ANcs3oSP23w9cpyL6LqNOFoAxMAfY25I-vNcURkTyB4=/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmVhdXRpZnVscHVibGljZGF0YS5jb20vY29udGVudC9pbWFnZXMvMjAyMy8wMi9TY3JlZW5zaG90LTIwMjMtMDItMTEtYXQtMTEuNTQuNDAtQU0ucG5n" alt="Pilot Manual for a 1940&#39;s U.S. Navy Blimp" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/XZvJseCEvkMmT8gvOcDR8KkSZ1d6Lnwg3WWLNmhbeyg=/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmVhdXRpZnVscHVibGljZGF0YS5jb20vY29udGVudC9pbWFnZXMvc2l6ZS93NjAwLzIwMjMvMDIvU2NyZWVuc2hvdC0yMDIzLTAyLTExLWF0LTExLjU0LjQwLUFNLnBuZw== 600w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/e6G_xYXB53p-aZQ-jhxyzsOW-x9DYx93RcAZROOuRr8=/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmVhdXRpZnVscHVibGljZGF0YS5jb20vY29udGVudC9pbWFnZXMvc2l6ZS93MTAwMC8yMDIzLzAyL1NjcmVlbnNob3QtMjAyMy0wMi0xMS1hdC0xMS41NC40MC1BTS5wbmc= 1000w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/ANcs3oSP23w9cpyL6LqNOFoAxMAfY25I-vNcURkTyB4=/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmVhdXRpZnVscHVibGljZGF0YS5jb20vY29udGVudC9pbWFnZXMvMjAyMy8wMi9TY3JlZW5zaG90LTIwMjMtMDItMTEtYXQtMTEuNTQuNDAtQU0ucG5n 1090w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px" loading="lazy"/><figcaption>The New York Times - <a href="https://nyti.ms/3liaRZp?ref=beautiful-public-data" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">July 31, 1943</a></figcaption></figure><p>The 40-foot long cabin, which sat nestled below the envelope could carry a crew of ten, and as weight was a key constraint, the manual listed the exact weight of each piece of equipment aboard, including the 85 lbs of canned and fresh food, 35 lbs of water and 16 lbs of rescue rations. A table of the electrical load analysis lists a “GE Grill - Stove - Oven” and a Manning Bowman #494 coffee percolator and an Everhot “roasterette”. Reading such hilariously specific data like this, I reassure myself that were I to ever acquire a time machine, and find myself piloting this blimp while hunting U-boats over the Atlantic in World War II, I’d know the exact amperage being drawn from the coffee maker (3 amps) if I needed to reduce power consumption in a pinch.  </p><p>The manual contains some beautifully executed cutaway diagrams with every single feature carefully annotated. When looking through this manual with its exquisitely drafted schematics, I thought about a used book I found a few years ago, “Illustrator Draftsman 3 &amp; 2” published by the U.S. Navy Training Command in 1972, which was an instruction manual for the kinds of artists and draftsmen in the Navy who probably worked on this blimp manual. This draftsman manual deserves a post of its own in the future.</p><p>The National Archives has some incredible footage of these K-Class airships in action. <a href="https://youtu.be/B0SYRukm6y0?ref=beautiful-public-data" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">One clip</a> is from December 14, 1943 and shows a crew aboard one of these blimps actually dropping depth charges on suspected submarines. There is also some incredible <a href="https://youtu.be/3bCOiF4kcqc?ref=beautiful-public-data" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">color footage</a> from 1944 showing one of these silver beasts taking off and landing on an aircraft carrier. </p><p>Seeing the crew members flying this behemoth really helped make these blimps come to life for me in a way I had not expected. </p><figure><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/TEbQ9wJJ2Wj5Pddbb8TpkCe2JXGqx3LKxm9qySCvgho=/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmVhdXRpZnVscHVibGljZGF0YS5jb20vY29udGVudC9pbWFnZXMvMjAyMy8wMi9TY3JlZW5zaG90LTIwMjMtMDItMTEtYXQtMi4xMi40MS1QTS0xLnBuZw==" alt="Pilot Manual for a 1940&#39;s U.S. Navy Blimp" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/-tYoDsc4ai7n7X6ebv-v9qG2u21G-j4giRDKluyhVRc=/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmVhdXRpZnVscHVibGljZGF0YS5jb20vY29udGVudC9pbWFnZXMvc2l6ZS93NjAwLzIwMjMvMDIvU2NyZWVuc2hvdC0yMDIzLTAyLTExLWF0LTIuMTIuNDEtUE0tMS5wbmc= 600w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/n6ve1uWPzEdCiuGLpF0rTwvRxWcaNgy9eYubAyEshVY=/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmVhdXRpZnVscHVibGljZGF0YS5jb20vY29udGVudC9pbWFnZXMvc2l6ZS93MTAwMC8yMDIzLzAyL1NjcmVlbnNob3QtMjAyMy0wMi0xMS1hdC0yLjEyLjQxLVBNLTEucG5n 1000w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/NZmVHVyb4oSd2COQ2MP_HCQqWJAa38KVhrLOS76jFgw=/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmVhdXRpZnVscHVibGljZGF0YS5jb20vY29udGVudC9pbWFnZXMvc2l6ZS93MTYwMC8yMDIzLzAyL1NjcmVlbnNob3QtMjAyMy0wMi0xMS1hdC0yLjEyLjQxLVBNLTEucG5n 1600w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/TEbQ9wJJ2Wj5Pddbb8TpkCe2JXGqx3LKxm9qySCvgho=/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmVhdXRpZnVscHVibGljZGF0YS5jb20vY29udGVudC9pbWFnZXMvMjAyMy8wMi9TY3JlZW5zaG90LTIwMjMtMDItMTEtYXQtMi4xMi40MS1QTS0xLnBuZw== 1775w" loading="lazy"/><figcaption>An cutaway view of the 40 foot long cabin. </figcaption></figure><figure><iframe width="200" height="150" src="https://www.youtube-nocookie.com/embed/3bCOiF4kcqc?feature=oembed" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen="" sandbo